100 Days of Code - Day One
--------------------------

Print commands-
E.g. print("Hello World")
Double quote in the bracket represensts the string to be outputed

If space is required between strings, it can be added by including a white space before or after the string or anywhere it is required. It can also be added by a whitespace between double quotes and concatinating it between the strings using "+" 
E.g. print ("Hello" + " " + "World")

Unnecessary indentation in the code can lead to indentation errors.

Taking end user input-
Input function is used for this functionality
E.g. input("What is your name?")

This input can be used to directly print user input using string concatination.
E.g print("Hello " + input("What is your name?"))

Adding comments in the code-
Comments can be added into the code via the "#". If a block or a line of code needs to be commented out, it can be done via the shortcut "Ctrl + /" after selecting the code.

Variables-
In simple words variables are a way in which we cans store user input or a predefined input in order to use it later.
E.g name = input("You Name:")

len() function can be used to find the length of a string.

Variable Naming Rules
- Make the name is clear and descriptive (readable)
- No whitespaces in betweenn (use underscores instead)
- No number in the begining
- Don't use priviledged words like print or input (or any other reserved words)
- Ensure that you only call variables that you have declared.
